        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Feb. 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> /1869</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your kindness is extraordinarily great about the Drosophyllum.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> If the Box (which if possible had better be covered only with bars?) must be addressed to some one in London, please address it to my brother’s House</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>“6 Queen Anne St.,</p>
<p>Cavendish Sq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>”</p> </figure> 
<p>Otherwise address it as at head of this note “per Rail”.— In either case please mark outside “<hi rend="underline">Living Plants, to be forwarded immediately</hi>”.—</p>
<p>You seem to be collecting numerous statements about the Dogs’ tails;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> suggest that you sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> keep a list of the cases, observing whether the dogs in the several cases are known <hi rend="underline">not</hi> to be related; for the number of cases alone w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be evidence of the intervention of some new cause.—</p>
<p>Did I mention in my former letter that I am very anxious to learn about the rate of development of the Horns in breeds of sheep in which the Rams alone are horned (viz merinos) &amp; in common breeds in which both sexes are horned,—especially if inhabiting same country &amp; fed in nearly the same manner.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> What ought to be observed, is, whether the horns are sensibly <hi rend="underline">larger</hi> or <hi rend="underline">smaller</hi>, at one or at two or at 3 months age, in the one breed than in the other. I hear from Saxony that in Merinos rams the horns can just be felt at birth.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I shall much like to hear your facts on the elimination under nature of disadvantageous variations.—</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours truly obliged | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>If you find the Dros. I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> much wish to know whether it grows in sandy, peaty or clay soil—whether damp or dry—whether sunny or shady.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
